p. The dative of purpose is, apparently, infrequent except in the gerundivo construction, which 10 commonly used:

fraudi cuiquam suit, Aua. 54; connmptui babuit, Aac. 93; iure 1111111110, Jul. 7.1; epistulis libellisque lepemlis . . . vacaret, Aua. 451.

b. The dative of the agent, socalled, is used for the ablativa of the agent:

campum Stellatem maioribus consecratum, Jul. 20.3; ara Octavio unsaramma 1.

i. The dative is used with siriuilis, even of persons, where the genitive is preferred in classical prose:

commotoque simiis, Aac. 51. 2.

j. The use of the dative with compound verbs is greatly extended :

monti mcubans, Jul. 41.1; adhibuit cenae, Jul. 733 tumulo . . . ascripserant, Aup. 123 Caesari inesse, Jul. 1. 33 insultaturum omnium capitibus, Jul. 22. 2; invecta urbi . . . pana, Auo. 41. 1.

lc. The dative is often used after verbs of separation and is - not limited, as in earlier writers, to persons:

coronae fasciam detrahi, Jul. 19.1; Antonium. . . . simulacro. .. abreptum, Aup. 11. 5; calorquere possessoribus proximos domos, Aua. 56. 2 ; eripere lepibus reum, Aup. 5113.
